Background

Crude oil is not only a highly volatile commodity, in terms of chemical properties and risk associated with price fluctuation (Peng & Li, 2020, p.4465), but also a vital element in global macroeconomics. Even though people are currently working hard on developing the alternate energy sourcing systems such as biofuel and hydrogen fuel and so on, petroleum still holds its place in many most important non-renewable energy resources in the world nowadays. Therefore, the prediction on the crude oil price around the world is essential. As law of one price is a most popular principle behind global trade, we will applied the law of one price to analyze the crude oil price between China (Importer) and the USA (exporter). Also, as exchange rate has a significant effect on the global market, the correlation analysis between crude oil and exchange rate will be developed.

Literature Review

According to the conclusion from Dr.Giulietti, the oil physical/chemical characteristics as well as the membership of OPEC will affect the crude oil price of trading based on 32 different global crude oil traded. Also, the differential are follow the law of one price principle (Giulietti and Iregui, 2015). Based on her outcome, we will located in two specific countries and to see if the law of one price also applicable during the pandemic.

Dataset

Data for Market Analysis - UN Comtrade for global market share analysis - OECD choose Australia, Japan, South Korea, Germany, America and Netherlands for price variety analysis - CEIC choose China for price variety analysis

Data for Law of One Price Analysis

  • Investing.com as export price from the USA
  • OECD choose Australia, Germany and Netherlands import price
  • CEIC choose China settlement price as import price
  • seadistance for shipping distance

Data for Correlation Analysis

  • Investing.com Factor: exchange rate between CNY and USD
  • Investing.com Factor: gold price

Roadmap and objectives

Firstly, we will use some visualization to show the mainly player in the crude oil market and the price changing along past 20 years

Secondly, we examines the relationship between shipping distance (in mile) and price spread (in USD). The shipping distances are collected from importing countries consist of Australia, China, German and Dutch, according to the data from OECD, Investing.com and CEIC in 2020. Also, a line graph is created to present the relationship between the movements in China and U.S. local crude oil futures prices, which is expected to help examine the degree of market integration. Given the deviation from what we would expect, the extended part of this section is developed with the collaboration of variables exchange rate and transportation cost in order to comprehend such anomaly.

Lastly, my team has run a few simple liner regressions to investigate the change rate in exchange rate and crude oil return, which deems to help further comprehend the exchange rate variable that is closely connected to various parts of this project.

Other than completed items listed above, the main objectives of this project are to provide and investigate, under Dr.Vercammans guidance, (1) the overview of global crude oil trade among major players, (2) how LOP applies in the syntax of crude oil industry and (3) how exchange rate interacts with crude oil futures prices for they are significant economic indicators.

An animation is created to demonstrate the changes in importing prices in the above importers across a 20-year timeline. In the animation, the import prices ranked from high to low are Australia, Japan, South Korea, Germany, China and Netherlands. As the worlds largest crude oil importer, China has the advantages in the price negotiation. Combined with its strategies in crude oil import, it is reasonable that the import price in China will be lower than the other Asian countries and even close to the European countries. unsurprisingly, the Americans import price is the lowest. 2. The Law of One Price Analysis

The spatial law-of-one-price (LOP) will be also examined in the crude oil trade between China and the United State. For a homogeneous good, trade between two countries occurs when their price difference is the same as the transportation cost, which is LOP (Stigler and Sherwin, 1985).

2.1 Price Difference V.S. Shipping Distance

If the law of one price hold, the price gap between exporters and importers should increase as the shipment distance goes up. We chose China, Australia, Netherlands and Germany to examine whether the LOP holds or not, since they can represent three various shipping routes. From the table, the country whose shipping distance is greater its price difference tends to greater at the same time.Therefore, we can roughly conclude that the LOP holds in this case study.

# create variable
US_exp_price <- 38.60

provlist2 <- c("CHN", "NLD", "AUS", "DEU")
imp_price <- Import_raw %>%
  filter(TIME == "2020",
         LOCATION %in% provlist2) %>%
  select(region=LOCATION, PRICE=Value)

Netherlands_dist <- 3411
Germany_dist <- 3785
China_dist <- 10638
Australia_dist <- 12873

# create df
imp_dist <- data.frame(region = c("AUS", "CHN", "DEU", "NLD"),
                          shipping_distance = c(Australia_dist, China_dist, Germany_dist, Netherlands_dist))

# create table
pdiff_distance <- imp_dist %>%
  mutate(import_price = as.numeric(imp_price$PRICE),
         export_price_US = US_exp_price,
         price_diff = import_price-export_price_US) %>%
  select(region, import_price, export_price_US, price_diff,shipping_distance) %>%
  arrange(price_diff) 

pdiff_distance <- pdiff_distance %>%
  kbl() %>%
  kable_material(c("striped", "hover"))

2.2 CNY Price Versus USD Price

For the further analysis on the LOP and the exchange rate effect, local price in China and USD were extracted to compared. Both of them are the price from local future exchanges, which will assist in reducing the bias. CHN_local was created to store the data of China and US_local stored the data of the United States. plot_china and plot_USA render the line graph of China and America separately.

With the comparing of these two graph, the movement and tendency of the price in CNY are similar to the changing of price in USD. The dramatic decreasing of the crude oil price in first half of 2020 is shown in both countries. However, the extents of fluctuations are not the same exactly, which means there are similar but not perfect match. Mr.Kaufmann and Mr.Banerjee explained the global market and price difference from various countries cloud be infludenced by physical, technical, political and economic barriers (2014), which can also indicate there are differences in the movement of crude oil price from various countries markets. Besides the factors mentioned by Mr.Kaufmann and Mr.Banerjee, we will try to use the movement of exchange rate to explained those variance.

It is interesting that this model can not only explain the law of one price is efficient in this study case but also relate to comment of pricing integration. In Module 1D, we know LOP is a significant assumption to pricing integration. Even their price movement are not exactly the same, it still represent pricing integration to a certain degree.

# load data
CHN_local <- read.csv(here("Data", "CN settlement price SH Furture Exchanges.csv"), header=TRUE, sep=",", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
CHN_local$Date <- seq(as.Date("2018/9/1"), by = "month", length.out = 36)
US_local <- read.csv(here("Data", "US Crude Oil WTI Futures.csv"), header=TRUE, sep=",", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
US_local$Date <- seq(as.Date("2018/9/1"), by = "month", length.out = 36)
US_local <- US_local %>%
  select(Date, Price)

# Create a data frame for price comparison analysis 
dfcu <- CHN_local %>%
  mutate(US_price = US_local$Price,
         CHN_price = Price) %>%
  select(Date, CHN_price, US_price)

# Plot the two price series side by side
plot_china <- ggplot(CHN_local, aes(x = Date, y = Price)) +  
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "Chinese Price", y= "CNY/barrel", x = "Date") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=10))

plot_USA <- ggplot(US_local, aes(x = Date, y = Price)) +  
  geom_line() + 
  labs(title = "American Price", y = "US$/barrel", x = "Date") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=10))

grid.arrange(plot_china, plot_USA, ncol = 2)

2.3 Analysis of Price Spread with Law of One Price

There may be almost 30% of the price difference can be explained by the transportation cost (Giulietti and Iregui, 2015). To test if the LOP hold exactly, we decided to analyze the price spread and calculate the arithmetic mean of the price spread to compared with the transportation cost. The data of price spread is irregular after 2020, which can be seen in the first picture.

# Import exchange rate data
exchange_rate <- read.csv(here("Data", "USD_CNY Data.csv"), header=TRUE, sep=",", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
exchange_rate$Date <- seq(as.Date("2018/9/1"), by = "month", length.out = 36)
exchange_rate <- exchange_rate %>%
  select(Date, exchange_rate = Price)

# Create a table contained price ratio and exchange rate
pr_er <- dfcu %>%
  mutate (priceRatio = CHN_price/US_price, 
          exchangeRate = exchange_rate$exchange_rate)
# Analysis of Price Spread
priceSpread <- mutate(pr_er, spread = (CHN_price/exchangeRate - US_price))

plot_Spread <- ggplot(priceSpread, aes(x = Date, y = spread)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Chinese - USA Price Spread", y= "US$/barrel", x = "Date") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=10)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(priceSpread$spread), color="blue")
plot_Spread

# focus on the data before April 2020
priceSpread2 <- priceSpread %>%
  slice(1:20)

To make the analysis proper, only the data before 2021 will be used. Finally, we found the mean is around $12, which coincides with the transportation cost reported by Bloomberg News during the trade war period (Cho and Cheong, 2020). That means the LOP hold efficiently in this analysis.

plot_Spread2 <- ggplot(priceSpread2, aes(x = Date, y = spread)) +

3. Analysis of the Exchange Rate Impacts

The change in exchange rate is an important factor to analysis the different between two local prices. Here, we isolate the exchange rate impacts to compare it with crude oil price ratio between these two countries. The data of exchange rate between CNY and USD is collected from Investing.com. Surprisingly, the differences in these two line graph are significant. The movement of price ratio rate is dramatically greater than the real exchange. And the index of price ratio is much higher than the exchange rate. That means when CNY strengthened against the US dollar, the weakened occurred in the local market price. Chinese importer are paying USD for their crude oil shipment and these USD are converted back to CNY the amount paid less. The huge movement of price ratio in the first half of 2020 might be caused by the trade war between the USA and China. Therefore, the difference of movement between Chinese price and American price can be partially explained by exchange rate but not all.

# Isolating the Exchange Rate Impact

plot_PriceRatio <- ggplot(pr_er, aes(x = Date, y = priceRatio)) +

3.1 Regression Between Change in Exchange Rate and Crude Oil Return

Our main topic is about the relation between the change in exchange rate and the movement in crude oil price. Firstly, a regression about how crude oil return can affect the change in exchange rate. However, the p value for estimator b_2 is too large. Therefore, we have no sufficient evident to conclude that there is a statistically correlation between crude oil return and the change in exchange rate overtime.

# Regression of Spread on Corn Transport Cost

3.2 Regression Between Change in Exchange Rate and Gold Return

Is it because crude oil has no direct relation with exchange rate? For further analysis, gold price was selected to do a similar regression as the previous one, since we know USD is pegged to gold. The data of gold price is collected from Investing.com. However, the model is still not hold. The return on gold have no strong relation with the exchange rate changing.

gold_price <- read.csv(here("Data", "Gold Futures Historical Data.csv"), header=TRUE, sep=",", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Conclusion

As stated in the introduction section, our conclusions drawn from this project also consist of three parts as following Firstly, within the scope of limited research in this project, the major countries that are significantly involved with global crude oil trade are often playing roles in both exporter and importer, which contributes to such rapidly changing global crude oil industry. Secondly, it is obtained a sufficient amount of evidences to demonstrate, in general, the spatial law of one price holds in the syntax of global crude oil industry. Thirdly, the exchange rate, surprisingly, is proved to be a significant factor when it comes to comprehend the dynamics of global crude oil prices in the local futures markets.

Limitation

As for limitations of this project, other than regression models are over simplified, our major limitations consist of the following two points: (1) it is assumed that U.S. crude oil futures prices are valid proxies for U.S. export prices, which seems unrealistic to my team. (2) my team chooses the local futures prices, other than import price and export price, in China and U.S. to examine the price dynamics, which is also a faulty assumption to make.
